  '["Abner turns against Ish-bosheth and promises to bring all Israel to David, but Joab kills him in revenge for Asahel''s death. David distances himself from the murder, laments Abner publicly, and refuses to let his own house appear guilty. The chapter strengthens David''s legitimacy while exposing the violence around him.", "When Ish-bosheth''s captains bring him the news of Abner''s death, two men murder him in his house and flee with his head. David again refuses to reward violence, executing the assassins and honoring the slain king with burial. The chapter removes Saul''s last rival by treachery rather than battle.", "The tribes finally come together and anoint David king over all Israel at Hebron. David captures Jerusalem from the Jebusites, makes it his stronghold, and grows stronger as the LORD establishes him. Philistine attacks follow, but David seeks God''s guidance and wins decisive victories.", "David brings the ark toward Jerusalem, but Uzzah dies when he touches it, forcing David to slow down and rethink reverence. The ark rests in Obed-edom''s house, then returns with joy as David dances before the LORD while Michal despises him. The chapter balances celebration with the fear of holy things."]'::jsonb,
  'Abner turns against Ish-bosheth and promises to bring all Israel to David, but Joab kills him in revenge for Asahel''s death. David distances himself from the murder, laments Abner publicly, and refuses to let his own house appear guilty. The chapter strengthens David''s legitimacy while exposing the violence around him.',
