  '["Abner turns against Ish-bosheth and promises to bring all Israel to David, but Joab kills him in revenge for Asahel''s death. David distances himself from the murder, laments Abner publicly, and refuses to let his own house appear guilty. The chapter strengthens David''s legitimacy while exposing the violence around him.", "David seeks the LORD and goes to Hebron, where Judah anoints him king, while Abner makes Ish-bosheth king over the rest of Israel. The chapter''s conflicts begin with a brutal contest at Gibeon and end with Asahel''s death and Joab''s hard-won victory. It shows a kingdom split before it is unified.", "When Ish-bosheth''s captains bring him the news of Abner''s death, two men murder him in his house and flee with his head. David again refuses to reward violence, executing the assassins and honoring the slain king with burial. The chapter removes Saul''s last rival by treachery rather than battle.", "David wants to build a house for the LORD, but the LORD instead promises to build David a lasting house and kingdom. Nathan relays the covenant that will outlast David''s reign and tie his line to future kingship. David responds with humility and awe, recognizing that God has spoken grace beyond his request."]'::jsonb,
  'Abner turns against Ish-bosheth and promises to bring all Israel to David, but Joab kills him in revenge for Asahel''s death. David distances himself from the murder, laments Abner publicly, and refuses to let his own house appear guilty. The chapter strengthens David''s legitimacy while exposing the violence around him.',
  'This advanced summary best matches 2 Samuel 3 (2 Samuel 3:1-21-2 Samuel 3:1-21).'
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
