  '["David defeats the Philistines, Moab, Hadadezer, the Arameans, and the Edomites, securing tribute from many surrounding peoples. He dedicates the spoils to the LORD and appoints officers over his expanding kingdom. The chapter shows a monarch whose victories are disciplined by worship and administration.", "David searches for anyone from Saul''s house to show covenant kindness for Jonathan''s sake and finds Mephibosheth, Jonathan''s crippled son. He restores Saul''s land to him and gives him a permanent place at the king''s table. The chapter turns royal power into mercy and memory.", "Amnon lusts after his half-sister Tamar, deceives her, and then hates her after violating her. Absalom shelters Tamar and quietly begins to nurse hatred against Amnon, while David is angry but passive. The chapter opens the final collapse of David''s family life.", "Joab uses a wise woman from Tekoa to press David to think about bringing back Absalom. David relents, but when Absalom is restored he remains half-healed and unsatisfied, living in Jerusalem yet not seeing the king''s face. The chapter shows reconciliation managed politically rather than spiritually."]'::jsonb,
