  'Which summary line best expresses the narrative function of 2 Samuel 16?',
  '["As David escapes, Ziba opportunistically claims Mephibosheth''s loyalty, and Shimei curses David with stones and dust. David refuses revenge and leaves judgment to God while Hushai arrives in Jerusalem to counter Ahithophel''s counsel. The chapter is full of mixed motives, but David keeps moving with restraint.", "Ahithophel gives Absalom a ruthless plan to strike David immediately, but Hushai gives a slower counsel designed to buy David time. The warning is carried through loyal messengers, and when Ahithophel sees his counsel rejected he goes home and hangs himself. The chapter shows wisdom fighting wisdom while God protects David through delay.", "David''s forces defeat Absalom''s army in the forest of Ephraim, and Absalom is caught in an oak by his hair. Joab ignores David''s plea and kills Absalom, ending the rebellion with a public heap of stones and a private father''s grief. The chapter is a grim climax where victory and sorrow collide.", "Joab rebukes David for grieving so hard that he seems to dishonor the men who saved him, and the king returns to Jerusalem after political confusion in Judah and Israel. The chapter includes tensions with Mephibosheth, the faithful support of Barzillai, and disputes over who truly stood by the king. David comes back to power, but the kingdom is still strained."]'::jsonb,
  'As David escapes, Ziba opportunistically claims Mephibosheth''s loyalty, and Shimei curses David with stones and dust. David refuses revenge and leaves judgment to God while Hushai arrives in Jerusalem to counter Ahithophel''s counsel. The chapter is full of mixed motives, but David keeps moving with restraint.',
  'This summary line expresses the narrative function of 2 Samuel 16.'
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
