  '["Joab rebukes David for grieving so hard that he seems to dishonor the men who saved him, and the king returns to Jerusalem after political confusion in Judah and Israel. The chapter includes tensions with Mephibosheth, the faithful support of Barzillai, and disputes over who truly stood by the king. David comes back to power, but the kingdom is still strained.", "Sheba son of Bichri sparks a northern revolt, and David''s new general Amasa is murdered by Joab under a pretense of greeting. The rebellion is contained after Joab pursues Sheba to Abel Beth-maacah, where a wise woman negotiates peace by handing over Sheba''s head. The chapter shows how fragile David''s restored kingdom still is.", "A famine reveals bloodguilt against the Gibeonites, so David hands over descendants of Saul and the land receives relief after justice is done. Rizpah''s vigil over the bodies moves David to gather Saul and Jonathan''s bones, and the chapter closes with battles against Philistine giants. Mercy, memory, and continued warfare all stand together here.", "David sings a long psalm of rescue, praising the LORD as rock, fortress, and deliverer who answered him in distress. The song celebrates God''s intervention in battle, his perfect ways, and his care for the humble. It becomes David''s theological summary of why he survived and ruled."]'::jsonb,
