  '["David orders a census, then recognizes that the counting was sinful and chooses to fall into the LORD''s hand rather than man''s. A plague strikes Israel until David builds an altar on Araunah''s threshing floor and offers sacrifices. The chapter ends with judgment checked by mercy and a site that will later matter deeply in Israel''s worship life.", "David''s last words celebrate the righteous ruler who governs in the fear of God and shines like the morning light. The chapter then lists his mighty men, honoring the loyal warriors who shared his hard-won victories. It closes David''s life story with both ideal kingship and remembered companionship.", "A messenger brings David news of Saul and Jonathan''s death, hoping for reward, but instead he meets grief and judgment. David composes a lament that honors Saul as Israel''s fallen king and Jonathan as his beloved friend. The chapter begins David''s reign with sorrow rather than triumph.", "David seeks the LORD and goes to Hebron, where Judah anoints him king, while Abner makes Ish-bosheth king over the rest of Israel. The chapter''s conflicts begin with a brutal contest at Gibeon and end with Asahel''s death and Joab''s hard-won victory. It shows a kingdom split before it is unified."]'::jsonb,
  'David orders a census, then recognizes that the counting was sinful and chooses to fall into the LORD''s hand rather than man''s. A plague strikes Israel until David builds an altar on Araunah''s threshing floor and offers sacrifices. The chapter ends with judgment checked by mercy and a site that will later matter deeply in Israel''s worship life.',
  'This summary captures the movement of 2 Samuel 24 (2 Samuel 24:1-9-2 Samuel 24:1-17).'
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
